snippet.textDisplay: If you want some named locomotives on the London Underground the 4 battery locos Metronet purchased for the 2006 refurbishment were named "Walter", "Lou", "Anne", and "Kitty".  ( Alf Arnold invented the names as a play on the line name. They were unusual in that the batteries could be removed by forklift and replaced by a charged spare. This stopped the locomotives being out of use while the batteries were being charged. Not sure where they are now - they were up for sale at one time. Perhaps Geoff can hunt them down and give one to Vicki for the LT museum.

I was in favour of the super sewer when I first heard about it, but then I heard about the £5bn pound price tag. Surely it's better just to live with the current river quality than be out of pocket by FIVE BILLION POUNDS??


This only really benefits people living near central london, so lets be generous and call that about 2 million. 5bn / 2 million = £2500 per person.

Do a poll on the people living near the Thames:
Would you rather:
Tolerate the current river quality?
or....
Pay an additional £2500 in tax to improve it?

snippet.textDisplay:
Small beer compared with coal mining. (But interesting all the same)
We were 700yds down at Hatfield and 3.5/4 miles from pit bottom. Proper locos too, 100HP six coupled Hudswell Clarkes. They are still down there, BTW.
Pits in the North East were twice that distance from the shaft. If memory serves Ellington held the record at 7.5 miles out from pit bottom, 7 of those miles being under the North Sea.
It really pisses me off when civil engineers trumpet their achievements. Tunnelling in London clay, or chalk marl for that matter, is easy. It takes the real skill of mining engineers and miners to drive tunnels through faulted ground at great depths.

snippet.textDisplay: I think naming a train "Vicki Pipe" is an excellent idea.  Our recently completed tunnel / subway boring machine was named Bertha after Bertha Landis, the first female mayor of Seattle.  This is an excellent and very worthy project.  I am amazed at the technology, engineering and work involved with all these projects.  London and England should be proud at the quality of these works.  I know a lot of folks moan, but until you have lived elsewhere and seen the shambles that represent the transport systems,  you do not know how good you have it

snippet.textDisplay: A minor point Marc Brunel created the first successful tunnel shield when he built the Thames Tunnel, the Greathead actually comes far later than Brunel's. Peter Barlow, actually comes next and was Greathead's teacher. Barlow makes the shield round and is the first to use the iron rings rather than brick to line the tunnel.  (I think this isn't bad for a Yank, who loevs the London Undergorund and and your videos, and dreams some day of doing an Amtrak All the Stations.)
